Seen in two groups.  The first group consisted of 7 macaws and flew over the main trail directly south of the Outlier and was heard & seen at 3:30 PM. A second group of 18 macaws flew over the main road where they had been seen a couple of weeks before.  This group we got excellent looks as they flew over the trail.  Ten Macaws of this second group landed on the top of a Polewood tree (Xylopia frutescens) where they were in plain view feeding on the fruit of this tree.  We were able to approach within 200 feet and even took some photographs of these colourful macaws.  Eventually these macaws were disturbed by our presence and raucousily departed.  	obs95599	Christopher 	Harris 	S5725117	eBird - Casual Observation	EBIRD_CAN				2	1		1	1

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS166918579	11590.35	species	Scarlet Macaw	Ara macao			80			Costa Rica	CR	Puntarenas	CR-P				PN Corcovado--Sirena	L446776	H	8.48025	-83.5893389	1996-06-16	06:00:00	Birding specifically for the Scarlet Macaw and observing behaviors and numbers along the Pacific Beach of Corcovado National Park	3 flocks of Macaws flew out during this morning at around 25-30 per flock.  Unfortuneatly I only had a pad and paper.  It was stated by our birding guide that this park was one of the last places in Central America to see wild Scarlet Macaws.  The early morning was relatively quiet but we hiked with our gear out to the beach to do the observations.  A flock of macaws would fly out....most in pairs, some single.  20 minutes would pass and another flock would come by and again we would count them in the air.  Each flock stopped along the canopy of the trees to feed on the local fruit and nut trees and would then continue further along the coast.  By mid morning, the 3rd and final flock flew out.  I finished my observations around noon and headed back for lunch.  We went for a swim and hike later that afternoon.  The Scarlet Macaws at this point returned back to Puerto Jimenez.  The flocks gathered in different clusters along the beach.  One flock perched high up onto a hillside.  A very loud gathering at the time.  It was my first outing with a professional birder.  While I took pictures, they are now what I'd call primitive and not very good.  However, in several I was able to capture the partial flock numbers.  Looking back on my photo documentation on at least two flocks, I could count 18-20 pairs.  Again the pictures are not complete but supports the evidence in my notes.	obs336013	Chris	Rohrer	S11824227	eBird - Traveling  Count	EBIRD	300	12.875		3	1		1	1

After one false start, we headed west through Atenas and Orotina, stopping there for the Black-and-white Owls in the town square.  A teen aged girl pointed them out, sitting right over our heads!  We ended at Rio Tarcoles, got a very basic room for 2 nights, had dinner and crashed.  Rooms had bad beds, lots of bugs, and fans that barely kept us cool.  Restaurant was excellent, cheap, good food and beer.  The crocodiles and the tourists were at the Tarcoles bridge.----4 March - Although it poured at midnight, it was dry at dawn and we were off to the Tarcoles bridge at 0600.  The Scarlet Macaws showed up right when the police officer on duty at the bridge predicted they would.  Birded a short trail behind the guard station.   Then birded the river trail with a guide, Freddie, until 1100, grabbed a meal at Los Crocodilos, and birded the headquarters trails by ourselves until 1730.  Found the manakin pool near dusk.   Day was hot, prob. 90, but not too muggy and few bugs.		obs141933	Bruce	LaBar	S10175866	eBird - Traveling  Count	EBIRD	540	8.047		2	1	G120618	1	0

From the Piro Research Center we walked west across the river and towards the main road.  A couple highlights included here were two Yellow-olive Flycatchers and Macaws feeding on teak seeds atop a tree. ------From here we walked into a clearing to the north where we came upon a Mangrove Cuckoo and White-necked Puffbird (nice views with both!) as well as a Long-billed Hermit nectaring on flowers.----Working north along the main road (245), we worked hard for a Lineated Woodpecker that was finally seen back up aside some dead limbs.  ----Our northward walk ended along an access road where we had our first, albiet brief, looks at a Black-cheeked Ant-Tanager skulking low in the understory.  A Riverside Wren was also seen near its nest.  Returned to Piro via the main road and picked up a Blue Dacnis just before we reached the river.		obs160024	Jennifer	Wenzel	S7599181	eBird - Traveling  Count	EBIRD_WI	195	1.046		13	1	G228605	1	0

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS90174071	11590.35	species	Scarlet Macaw	Ara macao			6			Peru	PE	Madre de Dios	PE-MDD			PE_14690	RN Tambopata--Cochachoca Lagoon	L890581	P	-12.8176849	-69.2617579	1987-06-23	03:30:00	with Ken Rosenberg, Thomas Laessoe, Chris Canady, Robin Welch. We left Explorers Inn at 3:30 a.m. to hike to Cochachoca Lagoon and arrive before dawn. We then took a small canoe out onto the lagoon, listened to owls & potoos, and watched dawn arive with flights of pigeons & parrots. Just a marvelous experience..... We stayed on lagoon until 9 a.m. (photos of Agami Heron, screamer, etc; heard Long-billed Woodcreeper, yet another potential lifer not included on the checklist) and then hiked in terra firma until early afternoon, returning back to Explorers Inn by 4 p.m.  Nice weather. The Scarlet Macaws, White-tailed Hawks, King Vulture, Horned Screamers, and duetting Russet-throated Puffbirds were the welcoming committee to the Hato, which has now been seized by the government of Chavez. The Oriole Blackbird, my first, was at a dusty rest stop about half-way through the trek. URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS90054377	11590.35	species	Scarlet Macaw	Ara macao			2			Venezuela	VE	Zulia	VE-V				Municipio La Cañada de Urdaneta, Campo Boscan	L889293	P	10.355	-72.1608333	2010-04-18	07:40:00	JosÃÂ© Gustavo and JosÃÂ© LeÃÂ³n, John KvarnbÃÂ¤ck, Karla PÃÂ©rez, Andreina Sojo, and I spent most of the day today at two adjacent ranches located about an hour southwest of Maracaibo, reached from the main highway off km. 56.  The first site (7:40 am - 12:00 pm), Hacienda La Modelo had mostly open pastures with scattered large trees, but also some marshy areas and a stripe of taller forest (with trees reaching maybe 20+ m in height) along a small river that apparently reaches the Sierra de Perija, with the forest sill continuous between the two (this representing the remnants of what was once continuous forest).  We spent an extended period of time in this forest looking for landbirds.  After checking Hacienda La Modelo, we cut over to Hacienda La Zuliana (12:05-3:25 pm), where we concentrated on a marsh with diked ponds that had much emergent vegetation, in places with cattails thickets, but also with grassy pastures.  We also spent some time here looking for land birds both in the scattered large trees and also a small patch of forest.  It was partly cloudy all day, with a mild (5-10 knot) breeze at times, high humidity, and temperatures probably increasing from the mid-70s to the mid-90s.  7:40 am - 3:25 pm.----Cathartes aura /burrovianus - 5;--Falco sparverius / columbarius - 1--(a small falcon brielfy as it flew off was either a Merlin (as John thought) or a kestrel (as I was leaning), but we saw no color or pattern on the bird);--Myiozetetes sp. - 4;----Hydrochaeris hydrochaeris - 1.
